    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2134405091" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2134405091" />
    <a title="Bbrown" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6261192-bbrown"><img alt="Bbrown" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1404741580p2/6261192.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2134405091?book_show_action=true">Oct 06, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bbrown" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bbrown" href="/user/show/6261192-bbrown">Bbrown</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2134405091" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11086958916433968080">Oe wrote Nip the Buds, Shoot the Kids when he was only 23, and, while that is impressive on its own, the book’s amateur nature unfortunately shows. <br/><br/>The basic story is that, concurrent with World War II, a group of what are essentially Japanese juvenile delinquents is evacuated to a rural village, and the villagers are none too pleased to have them. The comparison that I have seen most frequently made is to Lord of the Flies, but I think the similarities are largely only surface level, stemming f</span>
  <span id="freeText11086958916433968080" style="display:none">Oe wrote Nip the Buds, Shoot the Kids when he was only 23, and, while that is impressive on its own, the book’s amateur nature unfortunately shows. <br /><br />The basic story is that, concurrent with World War II, a group of what are essentially Japanese juvenile delinquents is evacuated to a rural village, and the villagers are none too pleased to have them. The comparison that I have seen most frequently made is to Lord of the Flies, but I think the similarities are largely only surface level, stemming from the little over a third of the book where the delinquents are abandoned during a plague outbreak. The go-to comparison for a bunch of kids left on their own is Lord of the Flies, but this is not a story of children trying to form a society that fails because of the children’s inherent nature, instead it’s the cruelty of the adult villagers that most drives the darkness of Nip the Buds, Shoot the Kids.<br /><br />Any book completed by a 23 year old is impressive to a degree, but, as previously mentioned, this is an amateurish work. The most prominent example of this work being a beginner’s effort from Oe is that at times he assumes that readers have an understanding of the book’s subject matter and so does not provide information. After having finished the book, I still have no clear grasp of the ages of the main characters. The narrator at times seems like he is eleven, other times like he is seventeen, and that’s far too large of a range. Relatedly, Oe is oftentimes stingy on providing character motivations and buildup to important actions, for instance when the narrator tries to hide the outbreak of plague and gets into a fight with a stranger over a bag of rice. You can cobble together logical reasons for the characters’ actions, but Oe doesn’t set them forth clearly. There are other problems as well, with some lines not making much sense (smacking of Oe or his translator trying too hard), and also the book abruptly ends with no resolution.<br /><br />This was the first book I read by Oe, and it may not have been the best place to start. Not only did he write it very early in his career, but I also understand it to be an outlier compared to most of his other works, as it is not autobiographical to some degree. This one is a slightly sub-par effort, and it does not lead me to expect greatness from Oe’s other books, but I should read one of his more famous later works before passing judgment. 2.5 stars, rounding up.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11086958916433968080" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


