<span id="freeTextContainer5374205021082272824">Personal response: <br/>This book is nothing compared to what it&apos;s like now than it was back then. I would give this book personally a three because of how it starts. The main kid out of the 15 is the best because of his intelligence and skills to build and problem solve.<br/>Plot Summary: <br/>This book Nip the Buds, Shoot the Kids starts out with one boy who is seeing harm in his village. Such as how the village is going down in animal population because they have been overtaken by soldiers. The boy gets mov</span>
  <span id="freeText5374205021082272824" style="display:none">Personal response: <br />This book is nothing compared to what it's like now than it was back then. I would give this book personally a three because of how it starts. The main kid out of the 15 is the best because of his intelligence and skills to build and problem solve.<br />Plot Summary: <br />This book Nip the Buds, Shoot the Kids starts out with one boy who is seeing harm in his village. Such as how the village is going down in animal population because they have been overtaken by soldiers. The boy gets moved to a different village where he finds his brother. His brother has an idea to get along with the black smith. Since the animals up in the mountains are dying, so the soldiers will too. They get 13 kids into helping them so this job can happen. The kids needed weapons for the journey to protect themselves. They asked the blacksmith if they can do something for him. Blacksmith used the kids to clean up dead animal bodies. They went to Jack, the blacksmith, after the kids cleaned up the dead animals. Jack then gave the weapons to the kids. Read the rest to find out what happens next.<br />Characterization:<br />The boy that the soldiers describe was a skinny but bulky kid that was on a mission. He didn't want to be stopped no matter what. He has brown hair, hazel eyes, and is always covered in dirt like he got in a fight.<br />The soldiers describe his brother with black hair, blue eyes, doesn't talk much unless is asked to, very strong even though he is younger than his brother. He wore a ripped up shirt everywhere he went too.<br />Recommendation:<br /> I would recommended this book to lots of people that are looking for adventure in their books. Also to keep up with all the back and forth in the book, the age limit should be 12 and up. Personally, I would like to give this book a 4.5 because of how lost I got in the beginning. I got out of that later on, and it was worth to keep reading.</span>
