<div id="review_135576036" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/135576036" />
    <a title="Thando" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3624747-thando"><img alt="Thando" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1271975058p2/3624747.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/135576036?book_show_action=true">Dec 18, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Thando" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Thando" href="/user/show/3624747-thando">Thando</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer135576036" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10416031080872212548">&quot;Nip the Buds, Shoot the Kids&quot; is the first novel written by Kenzaburo Oe at the young age of 23 (but then again you probably already knew this).<br/><br/>The novel is a harsh insight into the world of World War 2 Japan, and provides a deeply introspective satire and criticism of this Japan.<br/><br/>The stories protagonist an unnamed early adolescent boy is the engine of the story, propelling it forward through beautiful descriptions and anecdotes on japan at the time. A reformatory boy, being evacuated to the mou</span>
  <span id="freeText10416031080872212548" style="display:none">"Nip the Buds, Shoot the Kids" is the first novel written by Kenzaburo Oe at the young age of 23 (but then again you probably already knew this).<br /><br />The novel is a harsh insight into the world of World War 2 Japan, and provides a deeply introspective satire and criticism of this Japan.<br /><br />The stories protagonist an unnamed early adolescent boy is the engine of the story, propelling it forward through beautiful descriptions and anecdotes on japan at the time. A reformatory boy, being evacuated to the mountains along with his young brother and the rest of the fifteen strong group - he presents a moving and disturbing depiction of WW2 and japanese society.<br /><br />Japan has become blind and cruel, even children are treated as "vermin" in a country struggling to survive in a time of war. The isolated villagers (where Oe himself grew up) are characterized as vulgar, brutish and callous figures out for themselves.<br /><br />Often described as a Japanese "Lord of the Flies"; the book is a stunning commentary on WW2 Japan that provides the reader with a stark understanding of the fearful mind, and the beastly nature of war.<br /><br />A must read in a world where wars rage on endlessly... </span>
  <a data-text-id="10416031080872212548" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


