<div id="review_1194490850" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1194490850" />
    <a title="Ed Lehman" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11293317-ed-lehman"><img alt="Ed Lehman" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1346600279p2/11293317.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1194490850?book_show_action=true">Sep 25, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ed Lehman" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ed Lehman" href="/user/show/11293317-ed-lehman">Ed Lehman</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11293317-ed-lehman?shelf=1001-list">1001-list</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11293317-ed-lehman?shelf=completed-1001-list-book">completed-1001-list-book</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11293317-ed-lehman?shelf=asia">asia</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1194490850" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18038640228192907438">Having recently read William Golding&apos;s Lord of the Flies, it was easy to see the similarities with this tale: a group of boys forced to form their own society in order to survive. But whereas in the Lord of the Flies, the boys are marooned by an accident, these boys are deliberately abandoned by adults. The story takes place during war-time Japan and a group of reformatory boys are being evacuated to a mountain village.... only the village is being hit by a plaque killing animals and people alik</span>
  <span id="freeText18038640228192907438" style="display:none">Having recently read William Golding's Lord of the Flies, it was easy to see the similarities with this tale: a group of boys forced to form their own society in order to survive. But whereas in the Lord of the Flies, the boys are marooned by an accident, these boys are deliberately abandoned by adults. The story takes place during war-time Japan and a group of reformatory boys are being evacuated to a mountain village.... only the village is being hit by a plaque killing animals and people alike. The villagers eventually escape...and force the boys to remain by themselves. When the villagers return, the boys are again victimized. The novel is clearly a challenge to Japan's authoritarian tradition and the morality of the ruling class. Very well written and gripping. </span>
  <a data-text-id="18038640228192907438" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


